# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# stag  ("ssh to instance by tag")
#
# What it does:
#   Looks up an EC2 instance by its "Name" tag, grabs its public IP address,
#   and immediately opens an SSH session to it as the given user.
#
# How to run:
#   ./stag <ssh-username> <name-tag-value>
#   Example: ./stag ubuntu my-web-server
#
# Prerequisites:
#   - The AWS CLI v2 installed, with working credentials/region allowing
#     ec2:DescribeInstances.
#   - SSH access (key + security group) to the target instance.
#   - The tag should match exactly ONE running instance; if it matches several,
#     ssh will receive multiple IPs and likely fail.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Read the two command-line arguments into clearly named variables.
USER=$1   # first argument: the username to log in as
TAG=$2    # second argument: the value of the instance's "Name" tag

# Connect with ssh, logging in as $USER (-l) to a host computed on the fly.
# The $( ... ) is "command substitution": bash runs the inner aws command
# first and substitutes its output (the instance's public IP) as ssh's target.
#   --query : JMESPath expression pulling out just the PublicIpAddress field.
#   --filter Name=tag:Name,Values=${TAG} : keep only instances whose Name tag
#             equals the value you passed in.
#   --output text : print the IP as plain text so ssh can use it directly.
ssh -l $USER $(aws ec2 describe-instances --query "Reservations[*].Instances[*].PublicIpAddress"  --filter Name=tag:Name,Values=${TAG}  --output text) 
